    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-08T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-08T13:00:00-05:00" n="525"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">784A.561/7–1750: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Philippines</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-08T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 8, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>209. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 133, July 17.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d525fn1">Not printed; it reported that an Israeli representative had
                        been negotiating vainly with the Philippine Government for the purchase of
                        122 Sherman M–4 tanks (784A.561/7–1750).</note> Dept fully considered
                    aspects transfers M–4 tanks Israel. Regardless condition tanks Dept unwilling
                    consent shipment out of Far Eastern area such material which undoubtedly has
                    real war potential otherwise doubtful Israelis wld be interested. Dept’s info at
                    present time does not indicate Israel is at disadvantage militarily with respect
                    Egypt. Dept is permitting export from US quantities war material lesser mil
                    potential to Israel and: Arab states.</p>
                <p>US policy re arms shipments to <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>, as stated by US
                    rep in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Security Council at time <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> lifted embargo on arms to <gloss target="#t_NE1"
                        >NE</gloss>, limits such shipments to arms necessary for internal security
                    and self-defense. <pb facs="0990" n="968" xml:id="pg_968"/> Declaration three
                    foreign ministers made no change this policy. Dept, in fact, hopes Declaration,
                    in stating three-power concern for <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> security,
                    will increase confidence <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> states in future
                    security, and hence lessen need for large amounts of armament in area. In gen
                    Dept believes trend in <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> is away from war toward
                    peace.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
